        "The cost of a four-year college degree has become indefensible for the majority of Americans. Average student loan debt now exceeds $37,000 per borrower, with total outstanding student debt surpassing $1.77 trillion \u2014 more than credit card debt or auto loans. Tuition has increased 1,200% since 1980, far outpacing inflation and wage growth. The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reports that 41% of recent college graduates are underemployed \u2014 working in jobs that do not require a bachelor's degree.\n\nThe college wage premium is real but narrowing and misleading. While bachelor's degree holders earn a median of $1.2 million more over their lifetime than high school graduates, this figure averages together Harvard engineers with history majors from unranked schools. When you control for field of study and institution quality, many degree paths produce negative ROI. Georgetown's Center on Education and the Workforce found that 25% of workers with associate degrees earn more than 50% of workers with bachelor's degrees.\n\nAlternative pathways are proving their value. Coding bootcamps produce graduates earning $70,000+ within months at a fraction of college cost. Skilled trades \u2014 electricians, plumbers, HVAC technicians \u2014 earn median salaries of $56,000-$80,000 with minimal debt. Companies like Google, Apple, and IBM have dropped degree requirements for many positions. The fastest-growing occupations increasingly value certifications and demonstrated skills over four-year degrees.",
